node.text:
#AD100 firm Studio Peregalli’s atmospheric, enchantingly anachronistic style is, by definition, escapist, which is why it made perfect sense when a longtime client called on them to create a getaway on the shores of the Tegernsee, a lake in the Bavarian Alps. His brief for Studio Peregalli was to fashion an intimate bolt-hole for himself and some choice selections from his accumulated treasures. “The property sits between the mountains and a little lake, and it was designed very picturesquely,” he says. “It’s my private refuge."
.
See inside the home via the link in our profile. Photo by @robertrieger; text by @lauramaytodd; styled by Thomas Rook

When #AD100 architect @peterpennoyerarchitects was tasked with designing a home in the spirit of Czech Cubism, he and the homeowner felt free to play between periods and personalities since, in their brief heyday, Czech Cubists failed to produce a fully conceived interior. In the kitchen, stainless-steel, glass-front cabinets lined in @benjaminmoore’s Hancock Green mix with an island painted in Benjamin Moore’s White Diamond and a custom-made, red-enameled island range by @moltenistoves. 
See more of the home through the link in our profile. Photo by @williamwaldronphoto; text by @samuelcochran; styled by @michaelreynoldsnyc

Residential in feel with an exceptionally large terrace, the Paris atelier of #AD100 architect @luislaplace and his partner, Christophe Comoy (@comoylaplace) features a bespoke Laplace dining table and chairs in @lamaisonpierrefrey velvet. “Everything you see now is either new or restored,” notes Laplace, who closed off the main entrance so that you arrive via the garden, among other layout tweaks. “We changed the circulation, but the integrity was respected."
.
Discover more of the space through the link in our profile. Photo by @nicolas4matheus; text by @gaygassmann

In the New York apartment of #AD100 interior decorator Bunny Williams (@bunnys_eye), a hand-painted mural by @bobchristiandecorativeart covers an anteroom’s walls and ceiling, and a wood sculpture by Christopher Hewat hangs above English regency side chairs and an Indonesian soapstone rabbit sculpture. “Decorating a room is like making a great salad,” Williams says. “You want interesting ingredients." Discover more of the home via the link in our profile. Photo by @francescolagnese; text by @adaesthete; styled by @howardwchristian

French art dealer François Laffanour's (@laffanour_galeriedowntown) own collection—which comprises pieces by Ettore Sottsass, Pierre Chareau, Serge Mouille, Diego Giacometti, Martin Borowski, and Josef Hoffmann, among others—lines every floor of his charming Left Bank house. “I am an art dealer specializing in architects' furniture," he says, noting that his main interests are in the work of Charlotte Perriand and Jean Prouvé. One living room, above, is anchored by a Polar Bear sofa by Jean Royère, circa 1950, and a huge sculpture by the Portuguese artist @joanavasconcelosatelier.
.
Discover more of the home through the link in bio. Photo by @depasquale.maffini; text by @gaygassmann

In partnership with @indagaretravel, AD offers a series of curated trips around the world with an unprecedented level of access. On our upcoming journey to Tokyo this spring (May 12-17), guests will experience an insider’s view of the complex and layered metropolis, where time-honored traditions and futuristic innovation exist side-by-side. Hosted by Indagare founder Melissa Biggs Bradley (@indagareceo), and AD contributing editor @gaygassmann, the trip offers expert-led tours of top galleries and museums like the Tadao Ando-designed @21_21_design_sight, plus visits to some of Tokyo’s most intriguing private spots, including the flower studio of @azumamakoto, a botanical sculpturist who has been featured in the pages of AD. We will also stop at the Enoura Observatory to see its thought-provoking architecture and exposition spaces followed by a kaiseki lunch at a sleek @relaischateaux ryokan in the Fuji Hakone Izu National Park. Guests also have the option to extend the trip with a few days in spiritual sister city, Kyoto.

Learn more about AD’s insider journeys around the world and make your reservation today through the link in our profile. Photo by Jenna Neal on Unsplash #adxindagare

Two years ago, #AD100 interior designer Jacques Grange (@beaujolais1944) bought the apartment above his own that once belonged to the legendary writer Colette and made a duplex, with spiral stairs inspired by the curling Man Ray chandelier in his entrance hall. There was other major work to be done. On the lower floor, he replaced the leaky Belle Époque verrière with a new Cubist-style one after the Robert Mallet-Stevens–designed Villa Noailles in Hyères, and converted Colette’s (and his) bedroom into a guest room, above.

Take a tour of the home through the link in our profile. Photo by @francoishalard; text by @danathomasparis

“I kept thinking about what a New Yorker’s fantasy home in L.A. should look like,” says #AD100 designer Daniel Romualdez of outfitting a 1920s Spanish colonial property in the Hollywood Hills for real estate developer Will Bennett. “One of the nice things about Los Angeles is the weather allows you to shower outside,” says Bennett about this secluded corner of the garden, tucked behind an arched door whose purple color was inspired by the work of Mexican architect Luis Barragán.

Discover more of the home through the link in our bio. Photo by @yerinmok; text by @whatpaolasees; landscape by @sarita.jaccard.design

For a prominent art collector's Ohio countryside property, #AD100 architect @peterpennoyerarchitects crafted a family home in the spirit of Czech Cubism. A visit to Prague introduced the homeowner to the city’s obscure, short-lived (1911–1914) spin on the avant-garde movement, which yielded chiseled, seemingly charged buildings, paintings, and objects. “It was like learning a new language,” notes the Pennoyer, who worked closely with his firm’s design director, Gregory Gilmartin, to distill the movement into a language of facets and triangles. Above, Gothic-inflected arches draw the eye along the house’s main axis, and the pendant light is by @wokalampsvienna.

Visit the link in our profile to see more of the home. Photo by @williamwaldronphoto; text by @samuelcochran; styled by @michaelreynoldsnyc

For the grounds of her hilly property in Provence, #AD100 Hall of Fame interior designer Rose Tarlow (@rosetarlowmelrosehouse) handed over the seven and a half acres to the late Jacques Wirtz and his son Peter of @wirtz_international. The Antwerp-area firm’s hypnotic, suggestively surrealistic landscapes are largely flower-free demesnes that are studded with trees manicured into cloudy shapes and Buxus sempervirens coaxed into evergreen sculptures.

Take a look around via the link in our profile. Photo by @francoishalard; text by @adaesthete

Crossing the threshold of this Bavarian jewel box retreat by #AD100 firm Studio Peregalli, visitors are greeted by walls clad in 17th-century hand-painted blue-and-white Portuguese tiles, which, explains designer Roberto Peregalli, create a brightening “damask effect” in the otherwise shadowy entry hall. From there, a grand aged-wood staircase, lined with stately pilasters that frame the owner’s impressive collection of 18th-century architectural prints, winds up to the bedroom and private studio above.

See more of the home through the link in our profile. Photo by @robertrieger; text by @lauramaytodd; styled by @t_h_rook

When @davidlawenda and Kevin Menard (@menardeast) set out to build their dream Hamptons home from the ground up, they called on a dream team of designers, including architect Martin Sosa (@arcologicanyc), #AD100 interior designer @robertstilin, landscape architect Chris LaGuardia (@laguardia_design), and builder Tom O’Donoghue & Associates, Inc. “Everything we built, we built as a team,” Lawenda says of the intensely collaborative design process. “The property feels like a single idea, a single vision, because we pushed for a seamless integration of architecture, interiors, and landscape."
.
See the home via the link in our profile. Photo by @stephenkentjohnson; text by @mayer.rus

When Barry Schwartz, the cofounder of the Calvin Klein fashion empire, and his wife Sheryl acquired a beachfront plot of land in Santa Barbara, CA, they assembled a design team up to the task of conjuring an idyllic home worthy of the site and its myriad allurements. “Sheryl wanted it to feel unpretentious and completely appropriate for the beach, yet drop-dead chic," says Tommy Clements of #AD100 firm @clementsdesign. "That tension, between the elevated and the understated, animates the house." Above, @axelvervoordt chairs in a de La Cuona linen slipcovers surround a dining table by Joseph Dirand.

Visit the link in our profile to see inside the home. Photo by @wabranowicz; text by @mayer.rus; architecture by Howard Backen of @backengillamarchitects; landscape by Mark Rios of @rchstudios; styled by @amykchin

Back in 1977, a 22-year-old photographer named Mitchell Denburg touched down in the extravagantly baroque Guatemalan city of Antigua and started snapping. Besides the Spanish Colonial cathedrals and alluring landscape, the local serapes, or wool blankets, captivated Denburg's eye, too. Then a daydream suddenly kicked in: Why not start a weaving studio that would improve its workers’ standard of living while catapulting a Guatemalan tradition out of the country’s artesania shops and into international living rooms? Thus, in 1980, the @mitchell_denburg_collections was born. The little atelier that could started small (five workers, three looms) and grew big (today 175 weavers, 50 looms). Learn more about the Guatemalan weaving studio through the link in our profile. Photo by @a_gaut; text by @adaesthete

According to principal architect Jeanne Gang of #AD100 firm @studiogang, the American Museum of Natural History expansion is "the most exciting project [her firm] has ever done." Seven years in the making, Studio Gang finally broke ground on the Gilder Center this summer. Also in the works for the firm is the Vista Tower in Chicago, a new unified campus for California College of the Arts in San Francisco, and a new @phaidonsnaps monograph focusing on 25 projects, due in 2020.

Discover more designers and architects on the #2020AD100 list via the link in our bio. Photo via MIR and Studio Gang

Adulting looks different for everybody. For some it’s buying their first home. For others, such as 25-year-old @nyjah Huston, the Nike-sponsored American skateboarding phenom, it’s graduating to the second.

Watch the full Open Door tour of his Laguna Beach home through the link in bio. Text by @katromeyn

“Completely minimalist rooms give me apoplexy,” says #AD100 interior decorator Bunny Williams (@bunnys_eye). In the new apartment she shares with her husband, legendary antiques dealer @johnrosselli, Williams embarked on a swift, smart, and inspiring renovation. Moldings now ennoble the formerly detail-free walls, an aristocratic marble mantel went into the living room, and down went eye-catching carpets old and new (“I didn’t want to do sisal again,” the decorator says). In the library, above, a @penny_morrison_ltd linen wraps the walls, and the sofa is by @bunnywilliamshome in @lamaisonpierrefrey fabric and @claremontfurnishing trim.

Discover more of the apartment through the link in our profile. Photo by @francescolagnese; text by @adaesthete; styled by @howardwchristian

“[Sheryl] wanted the procession through the property to be very dramatic. When you reach a certain point, the ocean simply takes over,” says architect Howard Backen (@backengillamarchitects), describing the jaw-dropping 40-foot-wide, column-free expanse that connects the living/dining room of Barry and Sheryl Schwartz’s Santa Barbara home with the sublime natural vista just beyond. The hushed sumptuousness of the architecture and landscape is echoed in the assemblage of fine vintage furnishings by 20th-century masters mixed with companionable pieces by contemporary luminaries.

Take a tour via the link in our profile. Photo by @wabranowicz; text by @mayer.rus; interior design by @clementsdesign; landscape by Mark Rios of @rchstudios; styled by @amykchin

Real estate developer Will Bennett met #AD100 designer Daniel Romualdez five years ago while they were both working on 70 Vestry Street, a residential project in Tribeca. Not long afterwards, 30-year-old Bennett moved to Los Angeles and spent more than a year searching for his ideal home: a 1920s Spanish colonial property in the Hollywood Hills, with views of the city and a lush garden. “When I finally bought my new house, I jokingly asked Daniel if he wanted to work on it,” he says. “I’m so thankful that he actually said yes and kept to the budget—I think he even got excited about that!” For Romualdez, the idea of stepping outside of his studio’s norm was highly appealing. “It’s important for me to work with young people; it keeps me fresh,” he says.

Discover the project through the link in our profile. Photo by @yerinmok; text by @whatpaolasees; landscape by @sarita.jaccard.design

On AD Access trips, we take guests behind the scenes of the world’s most extraordinary design meccas. On our upcoming tour of St. Petersburg (May 8-13) , in partnership with luxury travel group @indagaretravel, we will explore the city's rich architectural past—from a VIP tour of the beautiful 18th-century Catherine Palace and its fabled Amber Room, to an after-hours visit to the famed Hermitage Museum (above), Catherine the Great’s former Winter Palace. Other highlights of the journey—led by AD’s Interiors & Garden editor Alison Levasseur (@alevasseur1) and contributing editor @howardwchristian, and @indagaretravel—include a private boat tour of the canals of St. Petersburg and meals at the city’s most exciting restaurants.

Learn more about AD’s insider journeys around the world and make your reservation today through the link in our profile. Photo courtesy of @hermitage_museum #adxindagare

#AD100 interior designer @olivermfurth is a true son of Los Angeles, deeply immersed in the city’s rich design history, from the tony mansions of Beverly Hills and Bel Air to the studios of the trailblazing artists and artisans who have colonized L.A.’s scrappy Eastside. Furth honed his skills working in the offices of some of Southern California’s most celebrated interior designers, including the late Greg Jordan, Michael S. Smith, Marc Appleton, Martyn Lawrence Bullard, and Trip Haenisch. His signature approach—a mix of freewheeling creativity and scholarly historicism— has been applied to a dizzying array of homes for Hollywood heavyweights.

Learn more about the #AD100 talent and see the entire #2020AD100 through the link in our profile. Photo by @stephenbusken

From @archdigestpro: In the latest episode of Behind the Design, #AD100 interior decorator Bunny Williams (@bunnys_eye) invites AD PRO inside the New York home she shares with husband, legendary antiques dealer @johnrosselli. Just as you’d expect, it's filled to the brim with delightful treasures and expertly curated vignettes; the couple’s pad is a veritable feast for the senses.

Watch the full video tour on AD PRO through the link in our profile. Film by @noeassociates

When @francoisemargueritelabro and her husband Philippe built a charming shingled cottage on the forested acreage they own in Normandy, they called on garden designer @louis_benech_officiel—now an #AD100 Hall of Famer—to craft the grounds into an evocation of an East Coast woodland. “My husband studied at Washington and Lee University in Virginia, and we got married in the Hamptons, so I said, ‘Let’s do an American house,’” says Françoise. Above, Benech edged a boardwalk with European live Oaks that have been pruned into lollipops. 
Click the link in our profile to see more of the garden. Photo by @photohaas; text by @adaesthete

Celebrating the best from the pages of AD over the past 100 years, our new book, “AD at 100: A Century of Style,” (@abramsbooks) is sure to delight any design lover on your holiday list. Inside, you'll visit the personal spaces of dozens of private celebrities like Barack and Michelle Obama, David Bowie, Truman Capote, David Hockney, and see in detail the work of top designers and architects like Frank Gehry, David Hicks, Oscar Niemeyer, Axel Vervoordt, Frank Lloyd Wright, and Elsie de Wolfe. Also included are stunning images from the homes of fashion insiders from Donatella Versace to Diana Vreeland. Pictured above is the living room of husband-and-wife photography duo Inez van Lamsweerde and Vinoodh Matadin (@inezandvinoodh) which was first seen in the October, 2011 issue of AD.

Learn more about the “AD at 100” book via the link in our profile or pick-up a copy wherever fine books are sold. Photo by @simonpwatson

At the heart of a prominent art collector's 140-acre Ohio countryside property sits a house designed by @peterpennoyerarchitects in the spirit of Czech Cubism. From the beginning, the client’s ambitions were clear: a traditional structure with stucco massing, crisp geometry, and neat symmetry. Like an iceberg, crystalline forms now emerge from the house’s limestone-trimmed stucco façades, beyond which arches, vaults, ironwork, moldings, and mantelpieces echo that vocabulary. “There is a lot of energy that comes from angles, but those forces equalize,” reflects Pennoyer, noting that the motifs feel carved, as if from a block of stone, rather than applied. “The whole project has a consistent calmness."
.
See more of the home through the link in our bio. Photo by @williamwaldronphoto; text by @samuelcochran; styled by @michaelreynoldsnyc
